Agrobacterium

-mediated transformation is the most common method for obtaining genetically modified plants. It is based on the ability of these soil bacteria to transfer one or more precise plasmid fragments (transferred DNA or T-DNA) into plant cells and to integrate them into the chromosomal DNA of the host (

).

After transfer, T-DNA genes begin to be expressed in the cells of the host plant, leading to the development of diseases called crown gall and hairy root (Chilton, 1980). These neoplasms represent transgenic tissues on a non-transgenic plant. The T-DNA genes can be roughly subdivided into three groups. The first one includes genes for the synthesis of opines, the products of which are used as nutrients by 

Agrobacterium

(Chilton, 1980; 

) but also play a role in various agrobacterial processes, like conjugation (

,b; Farrand, 1998) and quorum sensing (

). The second group influences morphogenetic processes in different ways (Garfinkel et al., 1981; 

; 

; 

). Some of them encode proteins for the synthesis of auxins (
iaaM
, 
iaaH
) and cytokinins (
ipt
) (Britton et al., 2008), others belong to a highly diverged gene family, and are called 
plast
genes (for phenotypic plasticity, 

). The role and mechanism of action of most of the 
plast
genes is still unknown or remains to be confirmed. A third group of genes have no homology to other genes, and their functions are completely unknown (

). Soon after the discovery of the T-DNA, several groups managed to replace the T-DNA genes by other sequences, and transferred them into plant cells using agrobacterial vectors. Subsequently, tissue culture techniques were used to obtain transgenic plants from such tissues (

).

The first naturally transgenic plants were found by chance within the genus
Nicotiana
.
N. glauca Graham
contains a cT-DNA (
), which is organized as an imperfect inverted repeat (Furner et al., 1986) and includes sequences similar to orf11 ( rolB ), orf12 ( rolC ), orf13 , orf14 , orf15 ( rolD ) and a mikimopine synthase gene ( mis ) similar to the one from pRi1724 (
). The
N. glauca
genes were called NgrolB , NgrolC , Ngorf13 , Ngorf14 , NgrolD , and Ngmis . Each gene, except NgrolB , is represented by two slightly different copies (Furner et al., 1986; Aoki et al., 1994;
). The cT-DNA was found in all
N. glauca
accessions, collected from several geographical locations. Thus, the transformation event most likely occurred before the formation of this species (Furner et al., 1986).
Nicotiana
is one of the largest genera in the Solanaceae and contains 75 species (Clarkson et al., 2004). Studies of the distribution of genes of agrobacterial origin in
Nicotiana
are summarized in detail in previous reviews (
; Chen and Otten, 2017;
). Horizontal gene transfer took place at least seven times during the evolution of the
Nicotiana
genus and may have contributed to speciation (
).

The development of molecular biology methods for efficient screening of genotypes for the presence of genes homologous to already known sequences, led to the discovery of a new example of a naturally transgenic plant within the genus 

Linaria

, among more than a hundred analyzed dicotyledonous species (

). This search for the presence of T-DNA-like sequences from both 

A. tumefaciens

and 

A. rhizogenes

was done using a modification of TaqMan-based real-time PCR (

) with degenerate primers and probes. This approach combines the positive features of PCR and DNA blot hybridization in a single reaction and allows the detection of sequences slightly different from those described earlier (

).

A cT-DNA was found in the genomes of different isolates of
Linaria vulgaris Mill
(toadflax) and
L. genistifolia
(L.). Mill. and characterized in detail (
;
;
). The
Linaria vulgaris
cT-DNA is organized as an imperfect direct repeat and contains sequences homologous to acs, orf2, orf3, orf8, rolA, rolB, rolC, orf13, orf14 , and mis . Certain genes from the cT-DNAs of
L. vulgaris ssp. acutiloba
and
L. creticola
have also been sequenced (
;
). Analysis of the rolC sequence from different toadflax species shows that all homologs can encode a full-length peptide. The rolC gene is the most conserved cT-DNA gene in
Linaria
(
;
).

Most cT-DNAs contain only opine genes, only few contain other gene 
types
(

; 

). There can be several explanations for this. First, in the course of evolution, growth-modifying cT-DNA genes could have been counter-selected, leaving only genes for opine synthesis.Secondly, since opine genes are often located close to the right border from where T-DNA transfer starts (

), incomplete T-DNA transfer could have favored their integration. Thirdly, some transforming strains may have carried simple T-DNAs with only opine genes. Another important conclusion from the earlier studies was that the opine synthase genes are more often intact than other T-DNA genes. This indicates that opine genes play an important role in the evolution of nGMOs. In this review, we will discuss the nGMO opine genes in detail. First of all, we will provide an overview of the opines and opine synthase proteins from crown gall tumors and hairy roots.

The first
Agrobacterium
-associated opine was detected in 1956 as a new type of amino acid derivative, present in large quantitites in sterile crown gall tumor tissue (
,
,
). The compound turned out to be related to N 2 -(1-D-carboxyethyl)-L-arginine or D-octopine (1) from
Octopus
, with L-lysine replacing L-arginine, and was therefore called D-lysopine (Biemann et al., 1960). Subsequently, lysopine synthesis and metabolism were studied (
,
;
). Later, crown gall tissues with lysopine were found to contain additional, structurally related compounds: octopine (M´enage´and
; Bielmann et al., 1977), octopinic acid (from L-ornithine, M´enage´and
), histopine (from L-histidine,
; Bates et al., 1984), and methiopine (from L-methionine, Firmin et al., 1985). Interestingly, octopine could only be detected after feeding tissues with L-arginine (
). All pyruvate derivatives are synthesized by a single monomeric 38 kD enzyme (Hack and
, 1980;
; Goldmann, 1977), called either octopine dehydrogenase, like the enzyme from
Octopus
(EC 1.5.1.11, Odh, ODH or OcDH,
), lysopine dehydrogenase (LpDH, EC 1.5.1.16) (to take into account the preference for L-lysine as a substrate, and the dominant opine in the tumors, lysopine), or octopine synthase (Ocs), the latter is now generally accepted.

A related product in which L-ornithine replaces L-arginine, was called nopalinic acid (4) or ornaline (Firmin and Fenwick, 1977; 

; 

). Initially, an « aline » family was proposed for nopaline and related compounds, but this was later abandoned. This creates some ambiguity, as the suffix -opine can be used for either pyruvate or α- ketoglutaric acid derivatives. Thus, histopine and methiopine are pyruvate derivatives, whereas leucinopine and asparaginopine are α- ketoglutaric acid derivatives.

Nopaline and nopalinic acid are synthesized by a 85 kD dimeric (

) or 138 kD tetrameric (Goldmann, 1977; 

) enzyme, using α- ketoglutaric acid, L-arginine, L-ornithine and NADPH as substrates.

The Mas2’ product dfg is unstable (

; Chilton et al., 1995). It is a natural Amadori compound and can also be found in rotting fruit and in the rhizosphere (Anet et al., 1957). Amadori compounds can be formed by non-enzymatic reactions between amino groups on free amino acids or proteins and reducing sugars. A free amino group reversibly interacts with the sugar to produce a Schiff base that may then undergo an essentially irreversible Amadori rearrangement, producing Amadori products such as fructosyl-amino acids (FA). The conversion of dfg into the more stable compounds mannopine and agropine by Mas1’ and Ags is of clear advantage to the agrobacteria Both mannopine, mannopinic acid and agropine undergo a non-enzymatic rearrangement to agropinic acid in aqueous solution, which may also occur 
in vivo
(Firmin et al., 1977; 

; 

).

N 2 -(1 ′ -deoxy-D-fructos-1 ′ -yl)-L-glutamine spiro -α- lactone (chrysopine) (15) is a δ- lactone of dfg (see above), and was first detected in Chrysanthemum tumors induced by strain IIBV7 (
). Chrysopine, dfg, and the dfg cyclisation product N -(1 ′ -deoxy-Dfructos-1 ′ -yl)-5-oxo-L-proline (isochrysopine), are Amadori compounds and derived from conjugates of D-glucose and L-glutamine (Chilton et al., 1995). Three genes coding for chrysopine synthesis ( chsC , chsB , and chsA ) are located on the TR region of strain Chry5 (
;
). The proposed pathway is the following: synthesis of dfg from D-glucose and L-glutamine by ChsC (a homolog of Mas2’),followed by lactonization of dfg by ChsA (a weak homolog of Ags) to chrysopine, a reaction similar to lactonization of mannopine to agropine. The role of ChsB (similar to Mas1’ in its N-terminal part) remains unknown (
). Chry5 tumors contain dfg and chrysopine, but no mannopine (Chilton et al., 1995).

Agrocinopines (abbreviated as ag) consist of four related structures. agA (16) and agB (17) were found by a bioassay in nopaline tumors induced by NT1(pTiT37) (Ellis et al., 1981), and in 15834 hairy roots (

), agC (18) and agD (19) occur in agropine tumors induced by Bo542 (Ellis et al., 1981) and in 8196 hairy roots (

). Agrocinopines are synthesized by Acs, but the reactions have not yet been elucidated. Structural studies showed that agA is a phosphodiester of sucrose and L-arabinose (linked between the 4-OH of the fructose moiety and the 2-OH of arabinose); its derivative agB lacks the glucose moiety (

). agC is a phosphodiester of sucrose and D-glucose (linked between the 2-OH of the glucose moiety and the 2-OH of glucose), its derivative agD lacks the fructose moiety (Dessaux et al., 1998). Glucose-2-phosphate esters are rare in nature (Zhang et al., 2020a. agA and agC are synthesized by agrocinopine synthases (Acs). Some strains, like C58, carry two intact 
acs
genes on their T-DNA, 
acs-2
is responsible for agA and agB synthesis (

), 
acs-1
cannot complement 
acs-2
and might have a different function, or be inactive (

). Other strains carry a mutated 
acs
version, like Ach5, AB3, and Hm1 (

). C58-Acs-1 and C58-Acs-2 are only 46% and 45% identical to Chry5-Acs. Thus, different T-DNAs encode highly diverse Acs enzymes, the catalytic properties of which remain to be elucidated.

Opines can be secreted or exudated from transformed tissues, which can be detected with different techniques. Agropine and mannopine secretion have been monitored by growth of tumor calli in liquid medium (
). Cell cultures of octopine and nopaline tumor tissues supplemented overnight with 10 mM arginine ( 3 H-labeled or non-labeled) led to the appearance of octopine and nopaline in the cell medium (
). A study of T-DNA mutants showed that expression of the C58 T-DNA gene 6a gene leads to increased secretion of octopine and nopaline, and 6a was subsequently called ons (for octopine and nopaline secretion) (
). The 6A protein belongs to the Plast group and does not carry obvious transporter domains. It may stimulate opine transport in an indirect way, which remains to be studied. Agrocinopine synthesis and agA secretion were detected in the same way by incorporation of
32 P.
Secretion of phosphorus by plant cells is very low, so that agA secretion is a highly significant phenomenon (
). Hairy root cultures transformed with different
A. rhizogenes
strains secreted agA and agropine (strain 15384), or agC and mannopine (strain 8196) in the medium (
).

